Hi <@UPDKXND6C> 
there were no pictures, because it was a discussion. I'll try to summarize here: 
• there are different flavors of performance testing: load, endurance, volume testing and many more depending on what is needed to be answered/discovered; they reveal different problems: e.g with endurance/soak testing memory leaks usually pop up;
• it is best if we can test on a production-like hardware, but if we can't, then the test env should be proportional with the production one; however we should always be aware of the risks and that extrapolation will never be precise and never the same;
• usually having "proportional" test env with lower resources may reveal some problems faster; by proportional we mean some general known correlations e.g. cpu vs memory; depends on what we measure;
• how do we calculate the target load? the easiest way is to search the production logs: find the usual peaks; if our software has never been live,  then there are calculations based on estimated user visits, concurrency etc.;
• we should be aware that users may not be the same as what we measure (e.g. requests per second), because one user may create multiple requests, so we should know our app: how end-user activities translate to requests/second, or kb/s if it is a streaming app etc.;
• we can do performance test on different levels: e.g. we can use our junit tests to see how performant is our algorithm; answer questions such as how long is the data processed from point A to point B, start up / shut down of a service, etc.;
• when we do load testing usually we are searching for a tipping point when the throughput cannot be increased more and response time is still acceptable; but how can we find this point if we are testing in an easily scalable environment? then our focus changes to detecting the metrics triggering the scaling, so we can improve them and reduce the need for scaling and save money, resources etc.;
• depending on the system there are usual issues that pop up and we firstly look for e.g. the load balancing configuration, db indexing and so on;
I think I haven't missed anything, but feel free to contribute or contact me for more discussions.
